  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems. Specific legal definitions can vary between jurisdictions, but typically include:\n\n1. Core elements:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming illegal money into seemingly legal assets\n- Disguising the origin of criminal proceeds\n\n2. Common legal components:\n- Engaging in financial transactions to hide illegal income\n- Attempting to make \"dirty\" money look \"clean\"\n- Transferring funds to obscure criminal origins\n\n3. Typical legal criteria:\n- Knowledge that funds are derived from criminal activity\n- Intentional efforts to disguise money's illegal source\n- Transactions designed to avoid reporting requirements\n\n4. International standards often include:\n- Currency transactions over specific monetary thresholds\n- Structured financial movements\n- Using multiple accounts or jurisdictions\n\n5. Key legal components typically include:\n- Placement stage (introducing illegal funds)\n- Layering stage (obscuring money's origin)\n- Integration stage (reintroducing funds into legitimate economy)\n\nThe precise definition can vary by country's specific legal statutes.",
